05583nam a22005055i 9780804767217DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047672177 a10.1515/97808047672172doi  a(DE-B1597)582256  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ767.5.C6bG74 2005 7aSOC0460002bisacsh04a363.9/6/09511 aGreenhalgh, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGoverning China's Population :bFrom Leninist to Neoliberal Biopolitics /cSusan Greenhalgh, Edwin A. Winckler. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (412 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Introduction: Population as Politics -- tChapter 2 Problematique: Governmentalization of Population -- tPart one. Policy Formulation and Implementation -- tIntroduction: Policy Actors and Policy Components -- tChapter 3 The Mao Era: From Soft Birth Control to Hard Birth Planning -- tChapter 4 The Deng Era: Rising Enforcement of Hard Birth Planning -- tChapter 5 The Jiang Era: Deepening Reform of Hard Birth Planning -- tChapter 6 The Hu Era: From Comprehensive Reform to Social Policy -- tPart two: Social and Political Consequences -- tIntroduction: Social Politics and Cultural Logics -- tChapter 7 The Shifting Local Politics of Population -- tChapter 8 Restratifying Chinese Society -- tChapter 9 Remaking China’s Politics and Global Position -- tChapter 10 Conclusion: Lenin, Foucault, and the Governance of Population in China -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChina's giant project in social engineering has drawn worldwide attention, both because of its coercive enforcement of strict birth limits, and because of the striking changes that have occurred in China's population: one of the fastest fertility declines in modern history and a gender gap among infants that is the highest in the world. These changes have contributed to an imminent crisis of social security for a rapidly aging population, provoking concern in China and abroad. What political processes underlie these population shifts? What is the political significance of population policy for the PRC regime, the Chinese people, and China's place in the world? The book documents the gradual "governmentalization" of China's population after 1949, a remarkable buildup of capacity for governance by the regime, the professions, and individuals. Since the turn of the millennium the regime has initiated a drastic shift from "hard" Leninist methods of birth planning toward "soft" neoliberal approaches involving indirect regulation by the state and self-regulation by citizens themselves. Population policy, once a lagging sector in China's transition from communism, is now helping lead the country toward more modern and internationally accepted forms of governance. Governing China's Population tells the story of these shifts, from the perspectives of both regime and society, based on internal documents, long-term fieldwork, and interviews with a wide range of actors—policymakers and implementers, propagandists and critics, compliers and resisters. This study also illuminates the far-reaching consequences for China's society and politics of deep state intrusion in individual reproduction. Like Mao's Great Leap Forward, Deng's one-child policy has created vast social suffering and human trauma. Yet power over population has also been positive and productive, promoting China's global rise by creating new kinds of "quality" persons equipped to succeed in the world economy. Politically, the PRC's population project has strengthened the regime and created a whole new field of biopolitics centering on the production and cultivation of life itself. Drawing on approaches from political science and anthropology that are rarely combined, this book develops a new kind of interdisciplinary inquiry that expands the domain of the political in provocative ways. The book provides fresh answers to broad questions about China's Leninist transition, regime capacity, "science" and "democracy," and the changing shape of Chinese modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aAnthropology -- Science, Technology, and Medical Anthropology. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Abortion & Birth Control.2bisacsh1 aWinckler, Edwin A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476721740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767217/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles